So the way this works today is, after image build we actually execute the tool (i.e. buildah) to query the version number.  When the reported version is new (tag doesn't exist in quay), we push it up then never ever touch it again (which may be why vulnerability scanning fails).  Since buildah in the container comes from a package (in the stable and testing images), bumping the version number actually means first releasing a new package (and going through the long list of related steps).

@rostrovsky since you're importing these into an internal registry anyway, is it conceivable you could periodically grab the stable:latest image from quay, but internally tag it with the complete buildah version?

It's possible [something here is broken](https://github.com/containers/buildah/actions/workflows/multi-arch-build.yaml), which I will investigate shortly...

> Unfortunately I work in tightly controlled environment

Understood.  The tagged images are driven by the available/released buildah package.  I see we have 1.21.2 in the updates-testing repo. but that has no hard-connection to pip updates (or anything else for that matter, unless it's an explicit dependency).

@rostrovsky can you check if `quay.io/buildah/testing:latest` has an acceptable version of `pip`? Better yet, can you can check to see that it passes all your validations?

Reason I ask is, it's entirely possible that a buildah 1.21.2 package goes from updates-testing into updates, triggers a new container image that still has an old version of pip (or something else that fails your checks).  Then, because of how we never again touch the version-tagged images, you're stuck :confounded: 

@rhatdan & @TomSweeneyRedHat I know we've been over and over this before...are you ***sure*** we can't change stance, and continuously push the version tagged images daily (esp. so we pick up security updates)?  In my mind, the version tag represents the buildah interface, not the rest of the container, so this /should/ be okay exception in my mind.
